SIMPLE: hedge
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hedge
<hw>Hedge</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>hegge</ets>,
AS. <ets>hecg</ets>; akin to <ets>haga</ets> an inclosure, E.
<ets>haw</ets>, AS. <ets>hege</ets> hedge, E. <ets>hay</ets>bote, D.
<ets>hegge</ets>, OHG. <ets>hegga</ets>, G. <ets>hecke</ets>. ⟦root⟧12.
See <er>Haw</er> a hedge.]</ety> <def>A thicket of bushes, usually thorn
bushes; especially, such a thicket planted as a fence between any two
portions of land; and also any sort of shrubbery, as evergreens, planted
in a line or as a fence; particularly, such a thicket planted round a
field to fence it, or in rows to separate the parts of a
garden.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The roughest berry on the rudest <qex>hedge</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Through the verdant maze⟦br⟧
Of sweetbrier <qex>hedges</qex> I pursue my walk.</q>
<rj><qau>Thomson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Hedge</xex>, when used adjectively or in
composition, often means <xex>rustic</xex>, <xex>outlandish</xex>,
<xex>illiterate</xex>, <xex>poor</xex>, or <xex>mean</xex>; as,
<xex>hedge</xex> priest; <xex>hedge</xex>born, etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Hedge bells</b></col>, <col><b>Hedge
bindweed</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a climbing plant
related to the morning-glory (<spn>Convolvulus sepium</spn>).</cd> --
<col><b>Hedge bill</b></col>, <cd>a long-handled billhook.</cd> --
<col><b>Hedge garlic</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a plant of the
genus <gen>Alliaria</gen>. See <cref>Garlic mustard</cref>, under
<er>Garlic</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Hedge hyssop</b></col>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a bitter herb of the genus <gen>Gratiola</gen>,
the leaves of which are emetic and purgative.</cd> -- <col><b>Hedge
marriage</b></col>, <cd>a secret or clandestine marriage, especially one
performed by a hedge priest.</cd> <mark>[Eng.]</mark> -- <col><b>Hedge
mustard</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a plant of the genus
<gen>Sisymbrium</gen>, belonging to the Mustard family.</cd> --
<col><b>Hedge nettle</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>an herb, or under
shrub, of the genus <gen>Stachys</gen>, belonging to the Mint family. It
has a nettlelike appearance, though quite harmless.</cd> --
<col><b>Hedge note</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The note of a hedge
bird.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>Low, contemptible writing.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Dryden.</au> -- <col><b>Hedge priest</b></col>,
<cd>a poor, illiterate priest.</cd> <au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>Hedge
school</b></col>, <cd>an open-air school in the shelter of a hedge, in
Ireland; a school for rustics.</cd> -- <col><b>Hedge sparrow</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a European warbler (<spn>Accentor
modularis</spn>) which frequents hedges. Its color is reddish brown, and
ash; the wing coverts are tipped with white. Called also
<altname>chanter</altname>, <altname>hedge warbler</altname>,
<altname>dunnock</altname>, and <altname>doney</altname>.</cd> --
<col><b>Hedge writer</b></col>, <cd>an insignificant writer, or a writer
of low, scurrilous stuff.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Swift.</au> --
<col><b>To breast up a hedge</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Breast</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>To hang in the hedge</b></col>, <cd>to
be at a standstill.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧While the business of money <xex>hangs
in the hedge</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Pepys.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hedge</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hedge
<hw>Hedge</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Hedged</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Hedging</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To inclose or
separate with a hedge; to fence with a thickly set line or thicket of
shrubs or small trees; <as>as, to <ex>hedge</ex> a field or
garden</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To obstruct, as a road, with a barrier; to hinder
from progress or success; -- sometimes with <xex>up</xex> and
<xex>out</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will <qex>hedge</qex> up thy way with thorns.</q> <rj><qau>Hos.
ii. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lollius Urbius . . . drew another wall . . . to <qex>hedge</qex>
out incursions from the north.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To surround for defense; to guard; to protect; to
hem (in).</def> ⟦ldquo⟧England, <xex>hedged</xex> in with the
main.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To surround so as to prevent escape.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That is a law to <qex>hedge</qex> in the cuckoo.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To protect oneself against excessive loss in an
activity by taking a countervailing action; <as>as, to <ex>hedge</ex> an
investment denominated in a foreign currency by buying or selling
futures in that currency; to <ex>hedge</ex> a donation to one political
party by also donating to the opposed political party</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To hedge a bet</b></col>, <cd>to bet upon both sides;
that is, after having bet on one side, to bet also on the other, thus
guarding against loss. See hedge{5}.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hedge</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hedge
<hw>Hedge</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To shelter one's self
from danger, risk, duty, responsibility, etc., as if by hiding in or
behind a hedge; to skulk; to slink; to shirk obligations.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I myself sometimes, leaving the fear of God on the left hand and
hiding mine honor in my necessity, am fain to shuffle, to
<qex>hedge</qex> and to lurch.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Betting)</fld> <def>To reduce the risk of a wager
by making a bet against the side or chance one has bet on.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To use reservations and qualifications in one's
speech so as to avoid committing one's self to anything
definite.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Heroic Stanzas read much more like an elaborate attempt to
<qex>hedge</qex> between the parties than . . . to gain favor from the
Roundheads.</q> <rj><qau>Saintsbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hedgeborn</ent>⟦br⟧
